   112	
   113	### Steps
   114	
   115	1. Create assistant and session store
   116	2. Call `assistant.useSessions(sessions)`
   117	3. Send inbound message with userId and surfaceId included in the envelope
   118	4. Verify assistant auto-creates a new session for the userId
   119	5. Send a second message from the same userId — verify the same session is reused
   120	6. Verify session is accessible in the message handler context (passed as part of handler arguments)
   121	7. Suspend the session, send another message from same user — verify session is resumed
   122	
   123	### Acceptance criteria
   124	
   125	- `assistant.useSessions()` plugin hook is implemented
   126	- Message handler context includes the resolved session
   127	- Session auto-create and auto-resume behavior is tested
   128	- Tests do not depend on any surface package being present
   129	
   130	---
   131	
   132	## WF-5: Attach surface and route messages
   133	
   134	**Package:** `surfaces`
   135	**Depends on:** surfaces-v1 spec, WF-2 (for `AssistantMessage` type shape)
   136	**Produces:** `SurfaceConnection`, `SurfaceConfig`, `SurfaceCapabilities`, inbound normalization, outbound formatting
   137	**PR scope:** `packages/surfaces/src/types.ts`, `packages/surfaces/src/surfaces.ts`, `packages/surfaces/src/surfaces.test.ts`
   138	
   139	### Steps
   140	
   141	1. Create surface connection for type "slack" with `createSurfaceConnection({ type: "slack" })`
   142	2. Create surface connection for type "web" with `createSurfaceConnection({ type: "web" })`
   143	3. Attach both to the assistant with `assistant.attachSurface(slackSurface)` and `assistant.attachSurface(webSurface)`
   144	4. Simulate an inbound event from the slack surface
   145	5. Verify inbound normalization produces a well-formed `AssistantMessage`
   146	6. Assistant processes and returns a response
   147	7. Verify response is formatted per the originating surface's capabilities (slack vs web differ)
   148	8. Verify response is delivered only to the originating surface (not fanout yet — that is WF-6)
   149	
   150	### Acceptance criteria
   151	
   152	- `SurfaceConnection`, `SurfaceConfig`, `SurfaceCapabilities` types are defined and exported
   153	- `createSurfaceConnection` factory is exported from `packages/surfaces/src/index.ts`
   154	- Inbound normalization contract is tested for at least two surface types
   155	- Outbound formatting contract is tested — slack and web produce different formatted output
   156	- `assistant.attachSurface()` plugin hook is implemented in core
   157	
   158	---
   159	
   160	## WF-6: Multi-surface session
   161	
   162	**Package:** `core` + `sessions` + `surfaces`
   163	**Depends on:** WF-4, WF-5
   164	**Produces:** cross-surface session attachment, surface-to-session binding
   165	**PR scope:** new integration test file `packages/core/src/core-sessions-surfaces.test.ts`
   166	
   167	### Steps
   168	
   169	1. Create assistant with sessions wired and two surfaces attached (slack and web)
   170	2. User sends message via slack surface — session is created, session.surfaces includes slack surface id
   171	3. Same user sends message via web surface — existing session is resumed, web surface is added to session.surfaces
   172	4. Verify both surface interactions share session state (same sessionId, same accumulated state)
   173	5. Assistant response targets the originating surface, not both surfaces
   174	6. Verify that detaching a surface removes it from the session's surface list
   175	
   176	### Acceptance criteria
   177	
   178	- Session correctly accumulates surface references across multiple surfaces
   179	- Response routing targets originating surface (not fanout to all)
   180	- Detach behavior is tested
   181	- No session duplication across surface-specific messages from the same user
   182	
   183	---
   184	
   185	## WF-7: End-to-end assembly
   186	
   187	**Package:** `core` + `sessions` + `surfaces`
   188	**Depends on:** WF-6
   189	**Produces:** integration test, validated assembly pattern, consumer-ready v1
   190	**PR scope:** new file `packages/examples/src/v1-assembly.ts`, new test `packages/examples/src/v1-assembly.test.ts`, updated package READMEs
   191	
   192	### Steps
   193	
   194	1. Full assembly matching the skeletal example from `docs/consumer/how-to-build-an-assistant.md`
   195	2. Define assistant with id, name, and capabilities using only public package APIs
   196	3. Wire sessions with `assistant.useSessions(createSessionStore())`
   197	4. Attach two surfaces with `assistant.attachSurface(createSurfaceConnection({ type: "slack" }))` and web
   198	5. Register a message handler
   199	6. Simulate a full cycle: inbound message → session resolve → handler → outbound response → surface format → delivery
   200	7. Verify the complete cycle produces the expected outbound shape
   201	8. Run the assembly with only v1 packages imported (no v1.1+ packages)
   202	
   203	### Acceptance criteria
   204	
   205	- Full end-to-end cycle is exercised in a single test
   206	- Assembly uses only `@relay-assistant/core`, `@relay-assistant/sessions`, `@relay-assistant/surfaces`
   207	- The test passes without any cloud, network, or external dependency
   208	- Package READMEs for core, sessions, and surfaces are updated with real API docs replacing placeholder text
   209	- v1 release tag is prepared
