 succeeded in 0ms:
     1	# V1 Sectioning and Priorities
     2	
     3	Date: 2026-04-11
     4	
     5	## Purpose
     6	
     7	This document defines what belongs to each version of the relay-agent-assistant SDK, using version-based sectioning language. It is the canonical reference for deciding which work is v1, v1.1, v1.2, and v2.
     8	
     9	---
    10	
    11	## v1 — Foundation
    12	
    13	**Scope:** The minimum skeleton that all product adoption runs on.
    14	
    15	**Success definition:** Sage, MSD, and NightCTO can `npm install` `@relay-assistant/core`, `@relay-assistant/sessions`, and `@relay-assistant/surfaces`, call `createAssistant()`, wire sessions, attach surfaces, and handle typed inbound/outbound messages without any additional packages.
    16	
    17	### v1 Packages
    18	
    19	| Package | What ships |
    20	| --- | --- |
    21	| `@relay-assistant/core` | `createAssistant`, `AssistantConfig`, `Assistant` interface, lifecycle (start/stop), `handleMessage`, plugin registration hooks |
    22	| `@relay-assistant/sessions` | `createSessionStore`, `SessionStore` interface, `AssistantSession` type, lifecycle transitions (created → active → suspended → resumed → closed) |
    23	| `@relay-assistant/surfaces` | `createSurfaceConnection`, `SurfaceConnection` interface, `SurfaceConfig`, `SurfaceCapabilities`, inbound normalization, outbound formatting, fanout model |
    24	
    25	### v1 Constraints
    26	
    27	- Pure TypeScript: all contracts are interfaces and types, no runtime framework dependencies
    28	- In-memory only: no network calls, no cloud service dependencies
    29	- Test-per-workflow: each workflow ships with at least one test file
    30	- No backwards-compatibility shims needed — this is greenfield
    31	
    32	### v1 Spec Documents
    33	
    34	Before any v1 code is written, three specs must be completed:
    35	
    36	| Spec | Path |
    37	| --- | --- |
    38	| core-v1 | `docs/specs/core-v1.md` |
    39	| sessions-v1 | `docs/specs/sessions-v1.md` |
    40	| surfaces-v1 | `docs/specs/surfaces-v1.md` |
    41	
    42	### v1 Workflows
    43	
    44	Seven workflows constitute the v1 build. WF-1 through WF-5 are the minimum shippable v1. WF-6 and WF-7 are integration stretch goals.
    45	
    46	| Workflow | Packages | Gates |
    47	| --- | --- | --- |
    48	| WF-1: Define assistant and start runtime | core | core spec |
    49	| WF-2: Handle inbound message | core | WF-1 |
    50	| WF-3: Create and manage sessions | sessions | sessions spec |
    51	| WF-4: Wire sessions into assistant | core + sessions | WF-2, WF-3 |
    52	| WF-5: Attach surface and route messages | surfaces | surfaces spec |
    53	| WF-6: Multi-surface session | core + sessions + surfaces | WF-4, WF-5 |
    54	| WF-7: End-to-end assembly | core + sessions + surfaces | WF-6 |
    55	
    56	### v1 Consumer Readiness Checklist
    57	
    58	By end of v1, Sage, MSD, and NightCTO teams must be able to:
    59	
    60	- [ ] `npm install @relay-assistant/core @relay-assistant/sessions @relay-assistant/surfaces`
    61	- [ ] Call `createAssistant()` with their product config
    62	- [ ] Wire a session store and attach surfaces
    63	- [ ] Handle inbound messages through typed contracts
    64	- [ ] Return formatted responses to the originating surface
    65	- [ ] Write product adapter code against stable v1 types
    66	- [ ] Run the SDK's own tests to verify correct integration
    67	
    68	---
    69	
    70	## v1.1 — Memory and Connectivity
    71	
    72	**Scope:** Persistence and focused inter-agent signaling. Unblocks Sage and NightCTO real-world utility.
    73	
    74	**Success definition:** Assistants can persist and retrieve memory across sessions. Multi-component assistants can exchange focused coordination signals over typed connectivity contracts.
    75	
    76	### v1.1 Packages
    77	
    78	| Package | What ships |
    79	| --- | --- |
    80	| `@relay-assistant/memory` | `createMemoryStore`, `MemoryStore` interface, memory scopes (user/session/workspace/org/object), retrieval and write contracts, compaction and promotion extension points, adapter interfaces for future backends |
    81	| `@relay-assistant/connectivity` | `createConnectivityLayer`, signal lifecycle state machine, suppression window semantics, `selected` audience resolution, escalation interface stub, coordination-connectivity interaction boundary |
    82	
    83	### v1.1 Connectivity Spec Gap Obligations
    84	
    85	The connectivity review verdict identified six open gaps. All six must be resolved in the v1.1 connectivity spec — not deferred:
    86	
    87	| Gap | Resolution |
    88	| --- | --- |
    89	| Signal lifecycle state machine | Define in `docs/specs/connectivity-v1.md` |
    90	| Suppression window semantics | Define in `docs/specs/connectivity-v1.md` |
    91	| `selected` audience resolution | Resolve jointly with coordination package owner, define in spec |
    92	| Connectivity-to-routing escalation interface | Define stub interface in v1.1; full resolution in v1.2 when routing ships |
    93	| Coordination-connectivity interaction boundary | Define call direction and owned interfaces in spec |
    94	| Four workflow specs | Write as `docs/workflows/connectivity-wf-*.md` |
    95	
    96	### v1.1 Consumer Notes
    97	
    98	- Sage needs `memory` immediately after v1 ships — v1.1 is the next critical gate for Sage adoption
    99	- NightCTO needs both `memory` and `connectivity` for multi-component assistant flows
   100	- MSD does not strictly require v1.1 for basic adoption but will benefit from `memory` for session continuity
   101	
   102	---
   103	
   104	## v1.2 — Proactive, Coordination, and Routing
   105	
   106	**Scope:** Autonomous behavior, specialist orchestration, and model-aware routing decisions.
   107	
   108	**Success definition:** Assistants can act without user prompting, orchestrate multiple specialists behind one identity, and make explicit model-choice and operating-envelope decisions through typed routing contracts.
   109	
   110	### v1.2 Packages
   111	
   112	| Package | What ships |
   113	| --- | --- |
   114	| `@relay-assistant/proactive` | `createProactiveEngine`, watcher and reminder contracts, scheduler binding interfaces over Relay substrate, evidence model for proactive decisions |
   115	| `@relay-assistant/coordination` | `createCoordinator`, specialist registry contracts, delegation plan and synthesis contracts, many-agents-one-assistant orchestration semantics |
   116	| `@relay-assistant/routing` | `createRoutingPolicy`, latency/depth/cost response modes, model-choice policy above raw provider clients, integration points for workforce workload-router style persona/tier resolution |
   117	
   118	### Why routing ships in v1.2 and not v2
   119	
   120	Routing contracts must exist before connectivity and coordination can make real depth/cost decisions. Deferring routing to v2 would force those packages to invent ad hoc routing assumptions that would need to be ripped out later. Routing is included in v1.2 to prevent that architectural debt.
